{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"b9a1e723-482d-47cb-a270-8c2a9d45352d","content":"Run **`dotnet workload update`**. Here's why:\n\n- **`dotnet workload update`** — Downloads and installs the **latest versions** of all installed workloads to match your current SDK. After an SDK update, this is what brings workloads (like `maui`) back in sync.\n\n- **`dotnet workload repair`** — Re-installs workloads at their **current versions**. It fixes corrupted installations but won't pull newer workload packages needed by a newer SDK.\n\n**TL;DR:** SDK moved forward → workloads need to catch up → `dotnet workload update`.\n\nIf the build still fails afterward, try:\n```bash\ndotnet workload update\ndotnet build\n```\nand check for any remaining errors.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"9caeecf9-700d-43d3-a51b-63d4bcf45c78","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about the difference between `dotnet workload update` and `dotnet workload repair` to fix a .NET MAUI build issue after an SDK update. This is a general knowledge question — I don't need to search any codebase for this.","outputTokens":251,"requestId":"A424:1F2F04:5F039B2:67712F0:69F00457"},"id":"2945a589-c6ea-42fd-905f-064b85a7d56d","timestamp":"2026-04-28T00:50:38.923Z","parentId":"cf4a46de-cdf3-4583-9590-74a7806fe872"}
